If you want to find specific threshold lambdas and lambdat for a given y, you can use a root-finding algorithm such as fzero or fsolve to find the solutions to the equation eval\_lambdas = 0 and eval\_lambdat = 0, respectively, where y is specified as a constant in the function.

For example, if you want to find the threshold lambda for a specific value of y, you can use the following code:

function zero\_eval\_lambdas = zero\_eval\_lambdas(lambda,cc,wbar,fc,r,y)
zero\_eval\_lambdas = eval\_lambdas(lambda,cc,wbar,fc,r,y);
end

lambda\_threshold = fzero(@(lambda) zero\_eval\_lambdas(lambda,cc,wbar,fc,r,y), initial\_guess);

Similarly, if you want to find the threshold lambdat for a specific value of y, you can use the following code:

function zero\_eval\_lambdat = zero\_eval\_lambdat(lambda,cc,wbar,F,r,y)
zero\_eval\_lambdat = eval\_lambdat(lambda,cc,wbar,F,r,y);
end

lambdat\_threshold = fzero(@(lambda) zero\_eval\_lambdat(lambda,cc,wbar,F,r,y), initial\_guess);

Note that the initial\_guess in the above code represents the initial value you need to provide to the root-finding algorithm to start the search for the solution. You can choose an appropriate value based on the range of lambda and the problem's characteristics.
